The content of curcumin in turmeric determines its color, quality, and therapeutic utility. Extraction of turmeric powder with methanol resulted in a yellow-colored pigment commercially known as oleoresin, the mother liquor of curcuminoids that becomes curcumin (
 Negi et al., 1999; 
 Teow et al., 2016). The extracted essential oils from turmeric powders through hydrodistillation were slightly viscous liquid with orange-colored, spicy odor, and insoluble in water characteristics. However, the essential oils are soluble in acetone and ethanol. Hence, a combination of both curcuminoids and essential oils had a wide range of biological activities including antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, anticancer, antimicrobial, neuroprotective, cardioprotective, radio-protective effects and anti-Alzheimer activities in both preclinical and clinical studies (
 Amalraj et al., 2017; 
 Meng et al., 2018).
